questionsAndAnswers.answer:
Complete conceptual implementation:

typedef enum { STATE_IDLE, STATE_HEADER, STATE_PAYLOAD, STATE_EXIT } StateId;
typedef StateId (*state_func)(void);

StateId do_idle(void) { return STATE_HEADER; }
StateId do_header(void) { return STATE_PAYLOAD; }
StateId do_payload(void) { return STATE_EXIT; }

void run_state_machine(void) {
    state_func state_table[] = { do_idle, do_header, do_payload };
    StateId current_state = STATE_IDLE;

    while (current_state < STATE_EXIT) {
        /* Dynamic jump using the function pointer array */
        current_state = state_table[current_state]();
    }
}

Implementation:

inline void vector_multiply(const float * restrict a, const float * restrict b, float * restrict result, int len) {
    for (int i = 0; i < len; ++i) {
        result[i] = a[i] * b[i];
    }
}

This function is marked 'inline' to eliminate call overhead. The restrict qualifiers promise that 'a', 'b', and 'result' all point to completely distinct arrays in memory. This guarantee allows the compiler's optimizer to generate high-performance SIMD instructions, performing multiple multiplications in parallel with registers, confident that a write to 'result[i]' will never affect 'a[i]' or 'b[i]'.

